      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">Marketing Copy · Ad Copy</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Copy</strong> is the written text used in marketing and advertising to persuade, inform, or drive action. It includes headlines, ads, emails, landing pages, product descriptions, and calls to action. Copy is judged by outcome — did the reader click, sign up, buy — not by literary quality. Distinct from <a href="/glossary/copywriting/">copywriting</a> (the craft), copy refers to the finished written asset.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Personalized CTA lift</div>
            <div class="tms-value">+202% (HubSpot)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Headline share of decision</div>
            <div class="tms-value">80% (Ogilvy)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Every button, headline, subject line, and product page carries copy. Most of it is bad, and the sites that fix theirs pull share from the ones that do not. Copy is the highest-leverage skill in marketing because it compounds — every visitor sees it, every campaign uses it, every test is a test of it.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is copy?</h2>
        <p>Copy is the persuasive written text a business uses across every marketing surface. It is the sentence a visitor reads first on your homepage, the subject line in their inbox, the button label on your pricing page, and the description under every product photo. Copy exists to move a specific reader closer to a specific action.</p>
        <p>Common surfaces where copy shows up:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ads</strong> — Google, Meta, LinkedIn, TikTok — headline + description + CTA</li>
          <li><strong>Landing pages</strong> — hero, subhead, feature blocks, testimonials, CTA</li>
          <li><strong>Email</strong> — subject line, preheader, body, CTA</li>
          <li><strong>Product pages</strong> — titles, benefit bullets, descriptions</li>
          <li><strong>UX microcopy</strong> — button labels, form hints, error messages</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why the headline carries the day</div>
          <p>David Ogilvy famously observed that <strong>80% of people who read a headline never read past it</strong>. Every dollar spent on driving traffic depends on the first ten words the visitor sees. Fix the headline before fixing anything else.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why copy matters</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Highest per-word ROI in marketing.</strong> A better headline lifts every downstream metric at once — CTR, conversion rate, revenue per visitor.</li>
          <li><strong>Compounds across channels.</strong> The same core value prop shows up on the ad, the landing page, and the email. Nail it once; lift everything.</li>
          <li><strong>Lowers CAC.</strong> Better copy raises <a href="/glossary/conversion-rate/">conversion rate</a>, which mechanically lowers <a href="/glossary/customer-acquisition-cost/">acquisition cost</a>.</li>
          <li><strong>Defines the brand.</strong> Voice, tone, and word choice are how customers experience the brand outside of visuals.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How high-converting copy works</h2>
        <p>Every piece of persuasive copy follows the same underlying pattern regardless of framework.</p>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-label">1. Attention</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Headline that names the reader's problem or promise<br>
          <span class="uf-label">2. Interest</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Subhead + hero that expands the promise<br>
          <span class="uf-label">3. Desire</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Proof — numbers, testimonials, screenshots<br>
          <span class="uf-label">4. Action</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> One CTA, one target, no ambiguity
        </div>

        <h3>Popular frameworks</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>AIDA</strong> — Attention, Interest, Desire, Action</li>
          <li><strong>PAS</strong> — Problem, Agitate, Solve</li>
          <li><strong>4Ps</strong> — Promise, Picture, Proof, Push</li>
          <li><strong>Before-After-Bridge</strong> — where they are, where they could be, how you get them there</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Types of copy</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Type</th><th>Surface</th><th>Primary goal</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Ad copy</strong></td><td>Google, Meta, LinkedIn ads</td><td>Click-through</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Landing page copy</strong></td><td>Dedicated conversion page</td><td>Conversion</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Email copy</strong></td><td>Newsletters, sequences</td><td>Opens + clicks</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Product descriptions</strong></td><td>Ecommerce PDPs</td><td>Add-to-cart</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>UX microcopy</strong></td><td>Buttons, forms, tooltips</td><td>Task completion</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>SEO copy</strong></td><td>Titles, meta descriptions</td><td>SERP clicks</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real copy examples</h2>
        <h3>1. SaaS CTA rewrite</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company changed the trial button from "Start Free Trial" to "Try Free for 14 Days. No Credit Card." Conversion lifted <strong>32%</strong>. Same offer, different frame — reduced perceived risk, added specificity.</p>

        <h3>2. Landing page hero swap</h3>
        <p>A B2B analytics tool switched from "The Data Platform for Modern Teams" to "See where your marketing budget is actually working — in 10 minutes." Trials rose <strong>47%</strong>. Generic beat specific never.</p>

        <h3>3. Email subject line test</h3>
        <p>An ecommerce brand A/B tested "Our March sale is here" against "Sarah, here's 20% off the [product] you saved." Open rate rose from <strong>16% to 38%</strong>. Personalized subject lines increase opens by 26% on average (Campaign Monitor).</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Copy vs content — same skill, different job</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Copy</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Drives a specific action</li>
              <li>Short-form (usually)</li>
              <li>Measured by conversion</li>
              <li>Lives on ads, landing pages, CTAs</li>
              <li>Every word must earn its place</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Content</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Educates, informs, or entertains</li>
              <li>Long-form (usually)</li>
              <li>Measured by traffic, time on page, ranking</li>
              <li>Lives on blogs, guides, videos</li>
              <li>Value comes from depth</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>Every serious marketing program uses both. Content brings people in through SEO and shares; copy converts them once they arrive.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 copywriting best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Lead with the reader, not the product.</strong> Change "We built the fastest CRM" to "Close deals without the admin tax."</li>
          <li><strong>Be specific.</strong> "10x faster" is stronger than "much faster." "$14,000 saved" beats "significant savings."</li>
          <li><strong>Cut every word that does not earn its place.</strong> Ruthless. Especially adjectives.</li>
          <li><strong>One page, one CTA.</strong> Multiple CTAs split attention and lower conversion.</li>
          <li><strong>Match voice to channel.</strong> LinkedIn is not TikTok. Same brand, different register.</li>
          <li><strong>Test the headline first.</strong> Highest leverage. Every other test comes second.</li>
          <li><strong>Read every sentence aloud.</strong> If it does not read out loud, it does not read on screen either.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — feature-listing without benefit</div>
          <p>"Real-time sync, 256-bit encryption, unlimited seats" is what your product does. "Your team stops missing deadlines" is what the customer buys. Every feature needs a because — because it saves time, because it reduces risk, because it prints revenue.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common copy mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Talking about your company instead of the reader.</strong> First-person plural should be rare in marketing copy.</li>
          <li><strong>Adjective stacking.</strong> "Cutting-edge, world-class, industry-leading" reads as generic. Specific numbers replace all of them.</li>
          <li><strong>Weak CTAs.</strong> "Submit" and "Learn more" leave conversion on the table. Tell the reader what they get.</li>
          <li><strong>Writing to yourself.</strong> Copy written for the internal team fails outside the office.</li>
          <li><strong>Never testing.</strong> The first version is rarely the best version — but only tests prove it.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between copy and content?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Copy is written to drive a specific action — click, buy, sign up. Content is written to educate, entertain, or build authority. A landing page headline is copy; a 2,000-word how-to guide is content. Best marketing programs use both — content to attract, copy to convert.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What makes copy convert?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Four things: a clear value proposition, specific numbers and proof, benefit-forward language over feature language, and a single unambiguous CTA. Personalized CTAs alone convert 202% better than generic ones (HubSpot).</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How long should marketing copy be?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>As long as needed and no longer. Complex or high-consideration purchases (B2B software, luxury) tend to reward longer copy. Impulse purchases and simple offers convert with short copy. Test — do not assume.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What are the best copywriting frameworks?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>AIDA (Attention, Interest, Desire, Action), PAS (Problem, Agitate, Solve), and 4Ps (Promise, Picture, Proof, Push) are the three most-used. Each works because it forces the writer to lead with the reader's problem before selling the product.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How do I test copy?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>A/B test the highest-leverage element first — usually the headline. Move to the CTA, then the hero subhead, then the offer framing. Aim for at least 100 conversions per variant before calling a winner. Track conversion rate, not clicks.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

